text: Please keep your conversations going.
Don't let me interrupt.
My name is James Early.
I work at the Center for Folklife and Cultural Heritage, where I serve as Director of Cultural Heritage Policy.
In a minute, I am going to be joined by Ms.
Gatoni Kamau, who is going to correct me in the, she said that was great.
I was about to say she was gonna correct me in the mastering of her name.
She is one of my colleagues.
here at the Smithsonian Institution at the National Museum of African Art, which is just across the way, and by Mr. Raymond Wong.
Would you please welcome Mr. Wong?
Yes, please.
And we're going to be talking about diasporas.

I was just thinking that when I began working at the Smithsonian Institution almost 40 years ago as a 26-year-old graduate student at Howard University, I was invited down to a meeting about the African diaspora.

And here I was, this young man, this African-American, I put that in quotations, invited to the very prestigious Smithsonian Institution, the mandate of which is the increase in diffusion of knowledge, and all of these scholars, and they said, we want you to work with us on the African Diaspora Program.
So I sat up and tried to look very intelligent.
I knew that the word diaspora meant dispersion, but I did not know how to connect it in any real way.

Because at that time, people talked about the Jewish diaspora, but it was not yet a term where everybody was talking about the spread of their cultures around the world in the very deep, formal, intimate way in which Jewish communities who had been dispersed around the world.
Now we have diaspora studies.
diaspora scholars and diaspora departments.
And if you put the word diaspora in your Google, it just pops up everywhere.
Well, we're going to talk about diaspora and identity.
Ms.
Katani Kamao works, again, as community outreach coordinator at the National Museum of African Art.
And she is originally from Kenya.
But I want to put that in quotation because we're going to find out
Is she from Kenya?
Is she still there?
Is she here?
How does that spread out?
Is that a place over there and she's here?
Are we living a new kind of sense of identity and reality?
And Mr. Raymond Wong, who started his group Wong People in 1985 in Chinatown, D.C., which is one of the hallmarks of inner city culture here in Washington, D.C.
Less than a mile, a nice little walk right up
7th Street here.
He's originally from Guangdong District, Hong Kong.
I hope I pronounced that appropriate.
He came to the United States at one years of age with his mother.
And his group performs dragon and lion dances at special events and gives free classes in Kung Fu and Tai Chi to everyone from the homeless to kids to adults to senior citizens.
Mr. Wong believes that martial arts teach individuals how the body works.
personal strengths and limits, self-defense skills, and how to use and understand your surroundings.
Welcome.
Let's start with Ms.
Gamow to tell us who you are, where you were born, what your relationship is to where you were born, and where you are.
All right.
Good afternoon, everyone.
Thank you so much for having me here.
It's great to be here this afternoon.
So I am born and raised in Nairobi, Kenya.
And I came here as an adult to attend a university.
And I ended up living in Pennsylvania, which is where I went to school.
ended up eventually staying and living and working in the US.
And the question was where I place my identity.
And it's very interesting because I am Kenyan,
by my formative years in Nairobi, going to school, high school, primary school, living in Nairobi, working in Nairobi, and then leaving as an adult to come out for higher education.
And you do become part of the new
country that you live in and you embrace it and become a part of that as well.
And so I see myself as African American.
I am Kenyan and I am American in many respects.
I have both cultures in me.
And so, you know, I feel in some ways I'm very, very Kenyan.
And in some ways, you don't know if that ever goes away because it was formed as your formative years.
So it is a part of just who you are.
And then, you know, as an adult, you embrace your new environment, your new culture.
And I am, when I go home, very American, you know, to my family and friends who are at home.
you have a duality, but at the end, I have myself, Gadoni, who I am as an individual, and that is the same regardless of which culture I'm living in and working in.
I do live and work here in the U.S., and so this is my home.
And I also think of Nairobi as home.
So I have two homes.
As we speak with Ms.
Kamau and Mr. Wong, I want you to be thinking about your identities.
What is your diaspora?
How do you describe yourself?
And I do want to come back to Ms.
Kamau in just a moment on being African American, but let's go to Mr. Wong.
Mr. Wong, tell us, when you came here, you came with your mother, did you have other family here already?
Okay, well, my father, he was actually born in Norfolk, Virginia.
You know, but traditional family, Chinese family.
His dad sent him back to China to get a wife.
So you see the connection there.
Back to the diaspora, yes.
Back to China to get a wife.
So I guess he got one, he hooked up, and a year later I was born.
Back then, China did not have open relations with the U.S., and people weren't able to leave and move about freely as they can now, and they really didn't have tourists.
That wasn't allowed back then.
That was in early 1960s, late 1950s.
So my mother escaped to Hong Kong,
as most Chinese and because back then Hong Kong was not under Chinese rule, it was under British rule.
So I was born in Hong Kong and I guess I'm British.
Yeah.
Yeah, I had to think about that.
Yeah, so I was born in Hong Kong.
So about almost a year later, because my father was an American citizen, his grandfather was a well-to-do Chinese restaurant owner here in Norfolk, Virginia.
And he's one of the first to open up a Chinese restaurant in Norfolk, because back then there weren't that many Chinese around, period.
So he got a good lawyer and filed the papers and got
my mom was both over to the U.S.
So I got here about one and a half and been here ever since and I guess I regard myself as an American citizen because
Educational-wise, financial-wise, credit card-wise, I have U.S.
Yeah, I'm USA.
But as far as my Chinese heritage, I try to maintain some of the teachings, some of the roots, and some of the practices that make Chinese people Chinese.
So what makes you who you are is not necessarily what government or what country you represent.
It's the way you live and your lifestyle.
and the background of your family.
So I try to maintain and live that as an American citizen, of course.
I can't think of a scholar who could have put it in a better theoretical or conceptual way.
Culture travels with you no matter what your passport.
says, how does that come up in your being Kenyan?

What are some of the cultural things that even as you describe yourself as an African-American are not historically associated with the evolved historical expressions and ways of knowing and doing of African-Americans who came here in the first instance as descendants of enslaved Africans?
OK.
So I consider myself an African-American, a Kenyan-American.
I'm not historically African-American in the context that you just described.
But as sharing part of the culture and just the way I live here in America,
It's the little things, like my colleague here was speaking about the food that I eat, it's very Kenyan.
Even though I've lived here so many years, there's some things that you say, I didn't get it.
What was the joke?
You just don't get some things.
I think in that context, you almost have to know more of the history or the context in which certain sayings or phrases come from.
And so, in that regard, you know, when I'm in Kenya, also, I'm like, what's that?
It's something new.
I don't know just because I live here, but in terms of

being, you know, like you are, culture is very dominant in us, I believe, as individuals and so it is part of who I am, just in my language, in my speech, in the food that I prepare, in dances, listening to music.
You kind of end up incorporating everything that you have and looking at
you know, the diaspora, the dispersion, it's all over the world.
It's almost like we're becoming this one global village, but you have your individual identities, we each have them, but the culture that's dominant within us is the one
We just immerse and thrive.
I mean, you know, America is special and unique in that it has every culture represented here.
So I'm looking for a certain spice.
I'll find it somewhere.
You know, I'll find it here.
And so, you know, I'm at home, equally at home here as I am in Nairobi.
I think for many African-Americans or black Americans of my generation, I'm just shy of 68 years of age.
It's a difficult thing, I think, and even for most of you.
We tend to think about our identity based on what we know about our parents, we perhaps knew about our grandparents, if we were lucky, what we knew about our great-grandparents.
And then we tend to place our identity in our actuarial chart of the hopefully 80 or so years that we're going to live.
But check this out.
Since the 1965 Immigration Act, more Africans have come to this country
than were brought during the entire period of slavery.
There were only approximately a half million enslaved Africans who were brought to the United States.
We look alike, but 50, 100 years from now, 200 years from now, a short time in human history, the culture, the ways of knowing and doing, because culture is alive, it continues to evolve.
This notion of African-American has been stretched.
Mr. Wong, when did you come to Washington?
This predominantly black city, I think, still is about 51 or so percent black, 70 percent black when I came here about 40 years ago.
Well, I arrived around 1958, 59, well, 58, yeah.
And I'm not sure if I can remember what it looks like back then, but it wasn't that black back then.
It was some, a lot of Jewish here back then, along with the black population.
Then right after the Martin Luther King riots, they became all black.
And when you started working in the community, talk to us about who you were working with and what were some of the cultural issues that you encountered.
Well, my father, he opened up a Chinese restaurant.
Because back then, either you had a Chinese hand laundry or a Chinese restaurant.
So he managed to get into the restaurant business in the corner of 2nd and Florida Avenue Northwest.
And that was black community.
So everything was catered to the black community.
It was an American restaurant, but it had Chinese food.
And the place was called Jimmy's.
Jimmy's, not a good American name.
So he sold not only Chinese food, but soul food.
Yes, Southern food.
And we were there.
Well, he was there, what, 1958?
I think I closed it down.
I didn't close it down, but I discontinued the food service around 1980, 1995.
All right.
I just moved on to other things.
But we served the black community for three or four decades.
Yes.
What kind of influence did it have on the way that you look at life, your taste, your interest, your sense of self-identity in this mix of Chinese and African-Americans?
Well, it just taught me some lessons that all people
have the same strengths, all people have the same weaknesses.
All people experience all things.
You just have to get to know them.
And the way you get to know them is you have to deal with them on a daily basis.
So me, having to work there, I have to deal with the customers on a daily basis.
I dealt with some really nice people, and I dealt with some really bad people.
I dealt with educated people, I dealt with drug addicts.
So I even had a gun stuck to my face a few times for holdup several times.
And I made it through that.
But you have to get to know the people, whoever they are.
And once we get to know them, then you understand.
Have you had the experience of new Chinese immigrants coming who became Chinese citizens, Chinese American citizens?
What has been your sense of your identity in relationship to them?
Are their sense of their identity in relationship to the kinds of history and experience that you come out of?
Well, the Chinese who are coming over now, they come over for opportunity.
They come over to start a business.
And that's good, but when you move into a community and you start a business, it's not just about selling something or providing a service.
It's also about getting to know the people.
Because if you get to know the people, then your business transactions will be a lot smoother than if you did not know the people.
Because it's that personal element that's missing that keeps business flowing smoothly.
So as far as the newer Chinese, the language barrier, that kind of keeps them from interacting with the customers.
So they just keep it at, OK, you want this?
Give me this.
It's $5.
And they just kind of leave it at that.
And a lot of times that causes friction in the community, because they feel, well, this
This foreigner is coming over to my neighborhood and making money off of me and I can't even get a good afternoon from them.
Well, they don't know how to say good afternoon, but it's the language barrier and the ability to interact with people on a level outside of business.
We're going to come to you shortly, not just with your questions, but your comments about diaspora, your own experiences, your own backgrounds.
But I want to ask each of you, starting with Ms.
Kamau, being out here on the National Mall, having Kenya and having China, what does that mean for you?
How do you feel about that?
All right, thank you.
It's great.
It's really a proud moment.
I'm like, oh, this is because, you know, this is the Smithsonian.
You have the best of the cultures being showcased in every aspect.
And people can interact, just like Raymond was saying, can go out and speak with the artisans, the participants.

It's not just pictures or something that you see on TV, but you can actually interact with the people and so that makes the experience all the more real and all the more inviting and a great experience for everybody all around.
So I feel great to be here.
I wish I could, you know, I'm at work, but I would love to come and spend and go to every single
demonstration and just visit and see what everyone is doing on a much more detailed level, but it's absolutely beautiful to see this Folklife Festival is absolutely beautiful.
Every year, it's different country, different culture, but that's what it's doing is highlighting it.
So I feel very proud to see all the artisans and all the culture portrayed and demonstrated the way it is.
And Mr. Wong, from Hong Kong to Norfolk to Washington, and then many diverse Chinese cultures within the national context of China are here on the National Mall.
What's been your experience in interacting?
Or have you had a chance to interact?
Well, yeah, definitely we need more events like these to bridge that gap with learning about each other and understanding.
So we learn enough, we can understand people.
It's that lack of information that causes problems.
Yes.
Questions, observations about your identities and diasporas.
Where do you come from?
Do you, when you say that you're an American or that you're from someplace else, what does that,

really mean in the 21st century with all of the movements of people and ways of knowing and doing that are not just bounded by being from Norfolk or being from Washington, but that you can find all over the world.
Any questions?
Observations?
Yes, ma'am.
Did you marry, are you married?
Yes, I am.
Okay, first of all, did you marry someone from here?
What is that person's identity?
Yes, I did marry someone from here.
I met her at a bar.
Yes, I did not marry Chinese, she's Filipino.
Right, so yes.
Will your kids carry on owning a restaurant?
Only if they want to do it.
You got to remember, restaurant work is long hours.
And that's why I got out of it, because I want to be able to come to events like these.
But if I ran a restaurant, I wouldn't be able to do it.
Yeah.
OK, so you married in a Filipina.
You're a Chinese-American.
How do your kids identify?
What is this term, Asian Pacific American?
What does that mean for you?
Well, it depends on the person, depends on the family upbringing.
It's not so much your race, it's not so much what you are called.
It's more your cultural practices and how you live.
What causes conflict is not what race you are or what you are called, it's your cultural practices.
Does this group's cultural practices conflict with this group's cultural practices?
That's what it's really about.
Can we get along in a working fashion, whether you're Irish or Russian or whatever?
Can we get along?
How close are our cultures?
So in your household food ways, is it
Is there one that dominates?
Well, Filipinos eat a lot of rice.
So Chinese eat a lot of rice.
Filipinos eat a lot of pork.
Chinese eat some pork, yeah.
Filipinos overcook their food.
Chinese cook it just right.
So we have some problems there.
And Filipinos eat a lot of sweets.
Chinese do not.
So we have some issues there.
And well, there's other things, too, but we're not going to get into that.
So just one last question to you before we go back to the audience.
So how old are your children?
And are they old enough where they are interacting and people say, who are you?
What are you?
How do they identify?
They were raised to keep an open mind, to accept people for their actions and not their labels.
Because at the end of the day, it's what a person does, what a person can accomplish.
It's not what they call you, because they can call you anything you want, but if you accomplish nothing, then we're zero, you know?
So it's a person's actions determine who they really are, and not what they're called.
Ms.
Kamau, is there a Kenyan community, not so much a fixed community, but associations or civic associations or cultural groupings that you are engaged with?
So there are very many cultural civic organizations based around church, around business, professionals.
And they are in the greater DMV area.
Actually, they're all over the United States.
And so I do interact with them.
I'm not a member of any one, but there are a lot of social,
activities and festivities around birth or weddings or just regular cultural things and a reason to get together and listen to Kenyan music, eat Kenyan food.
This is what draws the communities together and network as well.
So they do exist and they're very active within the groups as well.

I do also, I'm a member of African Immigrant and Refugee Foundation and so that services many different African populations and just assists with navigating as new Americans, teaching them how to just navigate the system and understand the different culture.
Among the older Kenyan citizens, residents here in the United States, you identify as African American.
Is there another dominant category or predominant category in how other Kenyans of Kenyan background might identify themselves?
Well, I do identify myself as Kenyan, but because I've lived here so long, I'd say, OK, I'm a Kenyan-American, and I'm from Africa, so I'm an African-American.
That is how I interpret it, because I'm like, that's what I am.
And so, sorry, what was the question?
No, that's good.
That's good.
Yes, sir.
Thank you very much.
Very interesting topics and the different type of presentations of the same topic from different viewpoints.
My name is Eduardo, and I am actually from Central America, Honduras.
And as far as the black diaspora, I am also a Garifuna, part of the Garifuna people out of Honduras.
And one interesting take is that when I came to this country
not being able to speak one word of English, the people who actually invariably embraced me were African Americans, as opposed to the non-African descendant or the non-Afro Latinos.
So ironically enough, I would like to ask the question, sort of, how, yeah, when you came here as an adult,
Who were you embraced by?
And even though you came in as a child, how were you embraced by, let's just say, the Chinese community, by the African American community, by others?
So when I came, I was a student.
So I was in university.
And at the time where I was, there was a very strong African Students Association.
And so I joined the association because that's what I identified with.
And so within that, for me, it was
I had met some different Africans from different African countries, but never so many in one place.
So that was where the primary embracing was.
It's a college town, and so within the college culture, the African Students Association was the cultural group that we cooked together.
And that's where, oh, you guys cook this?
You find out.
Oh, I know that word because of the Bantu languages have some root words in common.
And so for me, that experience was learning about the differences and the similarities.
Because for Africa, it has been in the past just like one, but it's so, so, so diverse, even within each nation.
So just learning those differences was wonderful.
And that's where I was embraced first.
Mr. Wong?
Uh, I can only speak, uh, when I first got here, I was like, uh, almost two.
So I don't remember that much, but if I just progress a little farther when I was five or six, um,
In my father's Chinese restaurant, the customers, I don't remember seeing any white people.
There were none.
There were no other Chinese people, so it was all black.
And we had a jukebox there.
I remember some of the songs, okay.
Fats Domino and different things like that, you know.
It was like five cents, you know.
And I used to sing there too, right next to Jukebox.
And the only white person I saw was the milkman, Embassy Dairy.
He delivered the milk to the restaurant.
It came in bottles back then.
And occasionally I would see a cop.
a white cop.
And for about a year, the other white person I saw was, I've got his name now, but he would pick me up and take me to this farm in Culpeper because my parents had to work.
They couldn't really take care of me at that age.
They couldn't watch me.
So they sent me there to live with this farmer in Culpeper.
So he would take me there.
He had other kids there, too.
So I guess they were in the same situation.
So he took care of me.
He took me away Monday through Saturday, and Sunday he would bring me back, spend the day.
So this went on for a couple of years, because my mother and father had to really work.
They worked like 14 hours a day in a restaurant.
When I got old enough, six or seven, I got my chores in a restaurant.
I had to do certain things.
I was a stock boy.
And back then, the only white people I saw were the cops and watching TV.
It was Chocolate City at that time.
It was really Chocolate City.
So, and it was tough getting along, I mean, well, getting by, because there weren't that many other Chinese there.
There's only a few.
The Hand Laundry, our restaurant, and the Chinese in Chinatown.
There weren't that many Chinese restaurants throughout the neighborhood like there is now.
So if a Chinese person walking the street, that's an odd thing.
That's really an odd thing.
And I got called all kinds of names based on what the latest name is at that moment.
There's a lot of different names they call you.
But it was a lot of slang thrown at me.
And so I went to public school down the street from where the restaurant was.
And I mean, according to my parents, I had a rough time there.
But I felt like it was OK.
I didn't know the difference.
But anyway, but that's pretty much my everyday environment during the 60s.
So in terms of growing up hearing Fats Domino, do you sort of feel like Fats Domino's music is your music?
It's not just those people's music?
Well, you got to remember, from the 60s all the way, the jukebox was there from the 60s to the 70s.
And then we got rid of it after the Martin Luther King riots.
Because, like, I remember, like, 10 people would come in with five cents to play one song so all 10 people can stand there and listen to it.
And they weren't buying anything else.
And my father's like, oh, you can't do that here.
Yeah, 10 people would get five cents to come and listen to one song.
And they would dance, and all the other customers were like, what's going on here?
I wanted some food.
So that's what happened then.
So there was a lot of artists from the early 60s to the end of the 70s, yeah.
Have you visited China as an adult?
Yeah, I went back in 1985, but it's different now.
Talk a little about that.
Well, I went back there in 1985.
It was still kind of hard to get in.
I mean, it's not as free as it is now.
It was a very, how do you call it?
I'm not going to say primitive, but it was very, I guess, country-like, most of China.
But it's totally different now.
This is just before they changed everything and built high-rises.
So when I went back there, it was
I remember the lack of toilets.
Yeah, everybody went on the side of the road.
Yeah, that's where they went.
And everybody was a vendor.
Everybody was a vendor.
And at that time, the Chinese who were from China, they went back as tourists.
There weren't that many Americans there at that time.
But now, I'm sure it's different.
Mr. Kamau, how often do you visit Kenya?
Not too often, but I was there last year in January.
I was there last year in January.
Did it have any particular sensory impact on you about being Kenyan slash black American here versus who Kenyans are today?
No, no.
Once I'm home, I'm just home.

You know, it's almost like when you're just in a different time zone, you're in a different culture, you just, after the jet lag, you just, you know, find out, you know, family members, catch up with family members and just,
Who are your family members, aunts, uncles, cousins?
Siblings, aunts, uncles, yes.
Friends.
It's very close.
You have siblings in other places on the continent of Africa and or Europe or other areas of the world?
No.
Well, I have other siblings here and in Kenya.

The reason I ask that question is one of the things that we're seeing in this new diaspora, Americans for many, many years, and some of you will be quite familiar with this, are right here on Capitol Hill.
Many Congress people have in the last 20 years said, I'm proud not to have a passport.
When I was a 19-year-old sophomore in the Panama Canal Zone in Central America with eight military U.S.
bases there, I would be hanging out with the G.I.s.
I was their age, but I was not a G.I.
I was a student.
And they would often say to me, hey, schoolboy, I won't see you for a couple of weeks.
I'm going back to the world next week, and I'll be back in three weeks.
That was a constant refrain.
I'm going back to the world.
which meant that I'm nowhere.
The United States was the world.
And my children at 38 and 35, my oldest lives in East London, has lived there for about 14 years.
I think we're seeing more U.S.
children now move around the world in the way that we have seen the rest of the world, particularly in the South, move a lot.
So, I mean, I have a lot of friends and relatives who live in different African countries or in Europe or anywhere in the world because of work.
of marriage, you know, just because.
Sometimes people just want to have a different experience.
So that, you're right, is much more common now than it ever was, you know, before.
So that definitely is.
And from the things that we're seeing out here, the songs, the dance, the crafts, the culinary traditions,
the skills, the knowledge base, that moves and it tends not to be just identified with a flag or with a national anthem or with a border.
We're seeing in the southwest part of the United States
people who go home and come home in the millions, hardworking people who are everyday neighbors.
And our laws are out of sync with our lived realities.
So before 9-11, this diaspora, something called the cedula matricula, an identification card, there was an accident.
People wanted to know about how can I do a blood transfusion, not whether I'm looking at an alien or an illegal or an undocumented.
seeing this push-pull and diaspora really is feeding that in new kinds of ways.
Other observations or questions from you?
You may have different views about this topic.
What diaspora are you from?
Where is your family background?
Does it stand outside the United States?
In the case of the Garifuna, a diaspora not only with regard to Africa, but starting in St.
Vincent and the Grenadines and Barbados, and you can find it in Honduras, and I think in Guatemala, and Nicaragua, and New York City is perhaps the largest of the Garifuna communities.
What is it to be a U.S.
citizen or an American?
Or what is it to be a Garifuna?
We are now learning, what is it to be Chinese or Kenyan or Black American?
The new lived realities in terms of our cultural ways of knowing and doing many, many things.
How are we on?
Oh, we got it.
So come on, folks.
I wanted to ask Mr. Wong, your experience growing up in Chocolate City, how has that affected at all your working with martial arts, and how did you get into martial arts?
Why martial arts, from cooking to martial arts?
Well, I got into martial arts because I was having some rough times at school in Chocolate City.
And of course I was watching TV and I see these guys kicking people and taking them out in like two or three moves.
I said, maybe I need to take some of that.
So I just went to Chinatown, of course.
Where else do I go, right?
Went to Chinatown.
They had a school just opening up at that time.
This was back in the early 70s.
And right around that time, that TV series came on with David Carradine called Kung Fu.
And back then, June Re was popular.
I remember TV Guide.
Your TV Guide, he always had an advertisement in there.
What, it was $12.95 or $19.95, and you get a bag and a uniform and a week's introductory lesson.
So I looked at that, I looked at all that.
I said, okay, maybe I need to do this, you know?
So I went down to take a lesson, and I just found it interesting.
I just kept on, and here I am today.
I have a school.
I hope this doesn't put Ms.
Kamau on the spot.
So you're at the National Museum of African Art in the capital of the United States of America.
So how many other African-born folk are working there?
Just myself?
I raise that question because one of the principles of this festival and the Center for Folklife and Cultural Heritage is issues of cultural democracy.
Speaking of these intersections of diasporas and identities, when I came to the Smithsonian Institution, there were hardly any African Americans in professional positions.
Now there are tons of them.
We were not even talking about
